## Element 1 — Executive Headline

### Rationale

This is the single most important element on the dashboard. It is the first thing the founder reads after what may be thirty to sixty minutes of completing four diagnostic tabs. It must immediately signal that the platform understood what they shared — not with a generic opener, but with a declarative sentence specific enough to feel earned.

The McKinsey framing is precise here: this is the headline that would appear on the first slide of a senior advisor's readout. It names the so-what of the entire portrait in one statement. It is not a greeting, not a label, not a section title. It is an insight stated as a fact.

**Section label:** None — this element has no section label. It sits at the very top of the content area without framing copy around it. The lack of a label is intentional — labeling it would reduce it to a section header. It is not a section. It is a statement.

**Layout:** Full width, immediately below the page header zone

**Component:** Single text element, no card container

**Data source:** `executive_headline` from view — GPT return field

**Behavior:**
- Renders only when `dashboard_status = 'complete'`
- No prefix, no suffix, no framing copy around it
- Stands alone as the opening statement

**Design:**
- Largest text weight on the page — this should read as the opening line of a document, not a subheading
- No card container, no background fill — sits directly on the page
- Full width with standard horizontal page padding
- Generous bottom margin before the Executive Summary section below

---

## Element 2 — Executive Summary Block

### Rationale

The executive summary unpacks the headline. While the headline is the so-what stated as a single declaration, the summary gives the integrated portrait: what kind of business this is structurally, what the logic is connecting the four dimensions, and what the dominant pattern looks like across the whole. It is not a sequential recap of the four tabs — it reads the business as a system.

Two to four sentences is the right constraint. Any shorter and it cannot carry the weight of the integrated portrait. Any longer and it starts to feel like a report introduction rather than an executive read. The founders reading this are sophisticated — they don't need explanation. They need characterization.

**Section label:** `YOUR BUSINESS MODEL` — small uppercase, muted, consistent with existing section label treatment

**Layout:** Full width, immediately below the executive headline

**Component:** Paragraph text block, no card container

**Data source:** `executive_summary` from view — GPT return field

**Behavior:**
- Two to four sentences rendered as prose — no bullet points
- No card container — sits as body text on the page with the section label above

**Design:**
- Body text weight and size consistent with existing prose blocks in the platform
- Standard line height for readability — this is a paragraph, not a data display
- Constrained max-width (approximately 70–75 characters per line) for optimal reading comfort — wider than this and comprehension degrades
- A subtle horizontal divider or increased bottom margin separates this from the Business Vitals Strip below, signaling the transition from narrative to data

---

## Element 3 — Business Vitals Strip

### Rationale

After two GPT-generated narrative elements, the vitals strip provides the data anchor. It tells the founder: the synthesis you just read is grounded in these specific numbers from your actual business. This is not opinion — this is what we computed from your inputs. The six metrics are chosen to collectively answer the five fundamental questions a sophisticated reader asks when scanning a business at a glance: how big, how efficient, how profitable, how structured, and how sticky.

Six was a deliberate choice. The prior version had eight and felt cluttered. At six, each metric has spatial room to breathe and the strip reads as a quick-scan data layer rather than a table. Cash runway was excluded because it is highly variable month to month and not always populated — anchoring a vitals strip on a metric that may be absent or misleading creates more risk than value. ACV was excluded in favor of churn rate because churn tells a more dynamic story about the business's ability to retain what it builds.

**Section label:** `BUSINESS VITALS` — small uppercase, muted

**Layout:** Full width, six cards in a horizontal strip

**Component:** Six metric cards

**Data sources — all deterministic from view:**

| Card | View Column | Display Format | Label |
|------|-------------|----------------|-------|
| 1 | `annual_revenue_run_rate` | $X.XM/yr | REVENUE |
| 2 | `annual_agi_run_rate` | $X.XM/yr | AGI |
| 3 | `profit_margin_percentage` | XX% | MARGIN |
| 4 | `total_team_size_fte` | X FTE | TEAM |
| 5 | `active_client_count` | Integer | CLIENTS |
| 6 | `monthly_churn_rate` | X.X%/mo | CHURN |

**Number formatting rules:**
- Revenue and AGI: if value is >= 1,000,000 display as $X.XM — if < 1,000,000 display as $XXXk — always one decimal place
- Margin and Churn: always one decimal place followed by %
- Team FTE: integer, no decimals
- Clients: integer, no decimals
- Null values: display `—` in place of the value, label remains visible

**Behavior:**
- All six cards render simultaneously when dashboard is complete
- No click behavior — display only
- No evaluative indicators — no color coding by performance threshold, no up/down arrows, no "healthy" or "concerning" labels

**Design:**
- Horizontal strip with equal-width cards
- Subtle vertical dividers between cards
- Value in larger numeral weight, label in small uppercase directly below
- No card borders on individual metrics — the strip reads as a single unified element
- Light background fill on the entire strip to visually separate it from the prose sections above and below

